c2Subcategories.label: Application Core and Lifecycle
c2Subcategories.description: Encompasses the main FastAPI application class, its constructor, and the ASGI interface for handling incoming requests and managing application lifecycle events.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To provide the foundational structure, configuration, and request processing entry point for the FastAPI application.

c2Subcategories.label: API Routing and Structure
c2Subcategories.description: Methods for defining HTTP and WebSocket routes, and for integrating modular API routers to build the application's endpoint structure.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To map URL paths to specific handler functions and enable a structured, modular approach to API design.

c2Subcategories.label: Middleware Management
c2Subcategories.description: Functionality for registering and applying middleware to intercept and process requests/responses globally.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To implement cross-cutting concerns like logging, authentication, and request/response modification.

c2Subcategories.label: OpenAPI Documentation System
c2Subcategories.description: Components responsible for generating the OpenAPI specification (Swagger/OAS) and supporting interactive API documentation UIs.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To automatically provide comprehensive, machine-readable, and interactive documentation for the API.

c2Subcategories.label: Request Parameter and Dependency System
c2Subcategories.description: A comprehensive system for defining, validating, and injecting various types of request parameters (query, path, header, cookie, body, file, form data) and managing dependencies. This includes parameter factories, their underlying classes, and OAuth2 form handling.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To abstract and standardize the extraction, validation, and transformation of incoming request data into usable Python objects for endpoint functions, and to manage reusable dependencies.

c2Subcategories.label: Response and Exception Handling Utilities
c2Subcategories.description: Provides specialized response classes for high-performance or alternative JSON serialization and the core logic for handling exceptions within the application.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To offer flexible and optimized options for formatting and sending API responses and to gracefully manage errors.

c2Subcategories.label: HTTP Endpoint Definitions
c2Subcategories.description: This subcategory encompasses the core decorators for defining HTTP GET, HEAD, and DELETE endpoints, along with the underlying generic route registration logic. It forms the public interface for standard HTTP API operations.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To expose API functionality via standard HTTP methods and manage their registration within the application's routing system.

c2Subcategories.label: WebSocket Endpoint Handling
c2Subcategories.description: This subcategory includes the decorators and internal functions specifically designed for defining and registering WebSocket communication endpoints.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To enable real-time, bidirectional communication by providing dedicated routing capabilities for WebSocket connections.

c2Subcategories.label: API Parameter & Dependency Management
c2Subcategories.description: This subcategory groups classes for defining various request parameters (e.g., Query, Cookie, File) and the mechanisms for dependency injection and security, including the base 'Param' class and 'Depends'.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To provide structured parameter validation, enable modular and testable code through dependency injection, and enforce security policies.

c2Subcategories.label: API Metadata & Response Utilities
c2Subcategories.description: This subcategory contains functionality for generating the OpenAPI schema (API documentation) and utility methods for rendering various types of API responses.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To automate API documentation for external consumption and to handle the final stage of response preparation and serialization.

c2Subcategories.label: API Endpoint Definition
c2Subcategories.description: Core methods for declaring HTTP and WebSocket endpoints, including their paths, response models, and OpenAPI metadata.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To expose application functionality through well-defined API interfaces.

c2Subcategories.label: OpenAPI Schema Generation
c2Subcategories.description: Functions dedicated to constructing specific parts of the OpenAPI specification, such as request body schemas and security definitions.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To programmatically build the OpenAPI documentation for the API.

c2Subcategories.label: Application Routing and Lifecycle
c2Subcategories.description: Manages the integration of sub-routers, registration of global exception handlers, and handling of application startup/shutdown events.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To configure the overall routing structure and lifecycle behavior of the FastAPI application.

c2Subcategories.label: Data Serialization and Transformation
c2Subcategories.description: Provides utilities for converting data types (e.g., Decimal to int/float) and for serializing/validating API responses according to defined models.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To ensure data is correctly formatted and validated when exchanged with clients or processed internally.

c2Subcategories.label: API Error and Exception Handling
c2Subcategories.description: Contains logic for handling various API-specific exceptions (HTTP, WebSocket), determining appropriate response bodies, and managing error reporting.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To provide robust and consistent error feedback to API consumers.

c2Subcategories.label: JSON Serialization Utilities
c2Subcategories.description: Handles the conversion of various Python objects, including Pydantic models, dataclasses, and standard types, into JSON-compatible formats. This is crucial for preparing data for API responses.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To provide a flexible and recursive mechanism for encoding complex data structures into a format suitable for JSON output, ensuring data integrity and proper representation.

c2Subcategories.label: Core Validation Exceptions
c2Subcategories.description: Defines the foundational exception classes for handling validation failures across the application, including specific types for request, response, and general validation errors.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To establish a standardized error reporting mechanism for data validation issues, allowing for consistent error handling and client feedback.

c2Subcategories.label: API Error Response Generation
c2Subcategories.description: Manages the process of catching specific validation exceptions (HTTP and WebSocket) and transforming them into structured error responses for clients.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To ensure that validation errors are gracefully handled and communicated back to the client in a standardized and informative manner, preventing server crashes and improving API usability.

c2Subcategories.label: OpenAPI Schema Generation
c2Subcategories.description: Responsible for introspecting API endpoint definitions and generating corresponding OpenAPI schema components, particularly for request parameters and examples.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To automatically create and maintain accurate API documentation (OpenAPI/Swagger) by extracting parameter information and examples from the code, aiding developers and API consumers.

c2Subcategories.label: Endpoint Configuration & Execution
c2Subcategories.description: Encompasses the mechanisms for defining API endpoints (e.g., PATCH operations), configuring their behavior (response models, dependencies), and executing the underlying business logic, including dependency resolution and error propagation.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To provide the core framework for routing requests, applying middleware-like configurations, resolving dependencies, and invoking the appropriate handler functions for both HTTP and WebSocket endpoints.

c2Subcategories.label: API Endpoint Configuration
c2Subcategories.description: Provides methods for developers to define and configure API endpoints, including specifying response models, status codes, and handling various response scenarios. This category sets the stage for how the API will behave and respond.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To enable the declarative definition of web API routes and their metadata.

c2Subcategories.label: Core Route Registration
c2Subcategories.description: Manages the internal process of registering defined API routes within the application's routing mechanism. It acts as the bridge between the high-level endpoint definitions and the underlying routing system.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To integrate API endpoint definitions into the application's request dispatching system.

c2Subcategories.label: Global Exception Middleware Setup
c2Subcategories.description: Responsible for building and configuring the application's middleware stack, specifically focusing on setting up global error and exception handling mechanisms that catch unhandled exceptions and server errors.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To ensure robust, centralized error management and consistent error responses across the entire application.

c2Subcategories.label: Request Handler Orchestration
c2Subcategories.description: Acts as a factory to create and configure the specific request handler for each API route, passing in route-specific parameters and integrating core processing logic.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To prepare and customize the request processing pipeline for individual API endpoints.

c2Subcategories.label: Endpoint Request and Error Processing
c2Subcategories.description: Contains the core logic for processing an incoming request for a specific endpoint, including parsing request bodies, resolving dependencies, executing the endpoint function, and handling immediate, localized validation and HTTP-specific errors. This is where many exceptions related to request data or HTTP status are first identified.
c2Subcategories.purpose: To execute the business logic of an endpoint and manage request-specific errors and responses.

c2Relationships.description: The core FastAPI application configures and manages the routing system by adding routes and including sub-routers.
The FastAPI core integrates middleware functionality, allowing global request/response processing.
The core application delegates exception handling to registered handlers.
The FastAPI application triggers the generation and serving of OpenAPI documentation.
API routes utilize the parameter and dependency system to define and validate endpoint inputs.
API routes produce responses and can trigger exceptions handled by the response and exception utilities.
The OpenAPI documentation system inspects parameter and dependency definitions to generate API schema.
Global dependencies defined in the parameter system are integrated into the application core.
Custom response classes are provided to the application core for use as default response types.
Specific HTTP method decorators (e.g., 'get') internally call more generic route registration methods to add the path operation to the router.
The public 'websocket_route' decorator utilizes an internal decorator function to encapsulate the logic for adding the WebSocket route.
Specific parameter types ('Cookie', 'Query') inherit from the base 'Param' class, and the 'Security' dependency mechanism extends the base 'Depends' functionality.

HTTP endpoint decorators are designed to accept and process parameters and dependencies defined by the API Parameter & Dependency Management components, although direct calls are not shown in these specific snippets.
The definitions of HTTP endpoints provide the essential information required for generating the OpenAPI schema and implicitly rely on response rendering utilities for output formatting.
Details from parameter definitions and dependency structures are crucial for enriching the OpenAPI schema with accurate and comprehensive documentation.
Endpoint definition methods (delete, head, websocket_route) register their routes with the underlying routing system, which is managed by the Application Routing and Lifecycle category.
Parameters provided to endpoint decorators (e.g., response_model, tags, summary, description, openapi_extra) are directly consumed by the OpenAPI schema generation process.
Endpoint definitions specify response_model and related serialization options, indicating that responses will be processed by data serialization functions.
The exception_handler method directly registers functions to handle exceptions, which are part of the API Error and Exception Handling category.
Functions like jsonable_encoder (implied by serialize_response and decimal_encoder context) are used by OpenAPI schema generation to encode examples and security definitions.
The http_exception_handler formats error responses, which involves serialization using utilities from the Data Serialization and Transformation category.
Utility functions like is_body_allowed_for_status_code are used within exception handlers, which are registered by the routing/lifecycle system.
API error handlers use JSON serialization utilities to convert exception details into a JSON-compatible format for client responses.
The OpenAPI schema generator uses JSON serialization utilities to encode example values for API documentation.
The WebSocket endpoint handler (`app`) raises `WebSocketRequestValidationError` (a core validation exception) upon encountering input validation failures.
API error handlers access the error details provided by core validation exception objects to construct informative client responses.
High-level endpoint definition methods invoke the core router implementation to register the route.
The route handler factory delegates to the core request processing function to handle the actual request logic.
Exceptions originating from endpoint-specific request processing are propagated and handled by the globally configured exception middleware.
